Walker argues that (1) the Territorial Court violated his Fifth Amendment Due Process Right and abused its discretion when, as punishment for asserting his right to a trial, the court sentenced him to twenty-three years for a first-time, nonviolent offense; (2) the court erred by refusing to include intent to defraud as an element of fraudulent use of a credit card under 14 V.I.C. Â§ 3004 (government confesses error on this issue); (3) Counts I and II alleging credit card fraud connected with the purchase of a single watch using two credit cards violated the Double Jeopardy Clause (government confesses error on this issue); (4) the court violated the maximum penalty provision of 14 V.I.C. Â§ 3010(b) by sentencing defendant to three separate (although concurrent) three-year terms for Counts I, II, and IV (government confesses error on this issue); (5) Counts III and V violated the Double Jeopardy Clause and the statutory intent of the Credit Card Crime Act and 15 V.I.C. Â§ 104; and (6) the Territorial Court erred by placing the burden of proving duress
