B. Counts Three and Five Are Void and Must Be Vacated because the Government Cannot Charge Appellant for Credit Card Fraud under Section 2101 (Possessing Stolen Property).
Walker argues that the Credit Card Crime Act ["CCCA"], Act of Feb. 28, 1972, No. 3171, Sess.
L. 1972, p. 26 (codified as 14 V.I.C. Â§Â§ 3001-3016), specifically 14 V.I.C. Â§ 3014, precluded the government from charging him for receipt or possession of stolen property under 14 V.I.C. Â§ 2101.
The long accepted rule, We next address the
asserted by the government, that a prosecutor may choose under which of two statutes to prosecute, also is not without exception.
The most obvious exception exists "where [the
Legislature] clearly intended that one statute supplant another."
See United States v. Sherman, 150 F.3d 306, 318 (3d Cir. 1998); see also United States v. Curran, 20 F.3d 560, 565 (3d Cir. 1994).
Legislative intent in this regard must be manifest in the
Walker v. Government D.C.
Crim.
App. No. 1998-196 Opinion of the Court Page 15
plain language of the statute or in a "positive repugnancy" between the provisions.
U.S. 114, 122 (1979).
The gravamen of Walker's argument is that the Virgin Islands Legislature intended to make the CCCA the exclusive basis for charging credit card crimes in the Virgin Islands.
5
See United States v. Batchelder, 442
He relies on
the plain language of 14 V.I.C. Â§ 3014, which bars application of any provision which is inconsistent with the CCCA: This chapter [sections 3001-16] shall not be construed to preclude the applicability of any other provision of the criminal law of the Virgin Islands which presently applies or may in the future apply to any transaction which violates this chapter, unless such provision is inconsistent with the terms of this chapter.
14 V.I.C. Â§ 3014 (emphasis added).
He argues, and we agree, that
14 V.I.C. Â§Â§ 3004 and 3010 (CCCA charging and penalty provisions, respectively) are inconsistent with 14 V.I.C. Â§ 2101 (possession of stolen property).
